Project Description:
We propose to develop quantitative, atomic-resolution methods for the three-dimensional characterization of complex semiconductor devices via electron tomography.  By coupling advance specimen preparation, cutting edge electron microscopy instrumentation, and AI-driven data collection and reconstruction, we will deliver a robust suite of measurement tools to the semiconductor industry, addressing multiple CHIPs grand challenges in the process.   

This project will:
·	Demonstrate the feasibility of sub-nanoscale and atomic electron tomography for real-world semiconductor device samples;
·	Use advanced data acquisition methods and reconstruction algorithms to achieve maximum contrast and spatial resolution in tomograms;
·	Develop data processing methods to extract quantitative metrics from ET 3D reconstructions;
·	Conduct live reconstructions during data acquisition at the microscope;
·	Research automation of ET workflow for industry;
·	Integrate AI-based approaches to data acquisition, processing, and reconstruction 
o	AI will be used to reduce noise in 3D tomograms
o	AI will be used to select specimen orientation to speed up data acquisition and reduce electron dose.
o	AI-based reconstruction models will be integrated with the data acquisition framework for live feed-back loop
o	AI framework still to be explored
o	New AI architectures with application to the 3D analysis of sub-nanoscale devices will be tested and implemented; and, 
·	Produce new measurement methods for immediate use by the semiconductor industry.
